## Cow and bull

@Perry1963 ([link](http://www.longwood.edu/staff/isaacsw/Examship.pdf))

- cow (pure): data, however relevant, without concepts
<#pause>

    - e.g. "*H. neanderthalensis* went extinct about 30 kya"
- bull (pure): concepts, however relevant, without data
<#pause>	
    - e.g. "climate change is a potential cause of species extinction"

essay questions favour bull, multiple choice questions favour cow

## Thinking about biology: adaptationism

* avoid adaptationist/*Just-So stories*
* @nielsen_adaptionism30_2009: "the combination of a functional effect and selection does not demonstrate that selection acted on the specific trait in question"
* "specific historical evolutionary hypotheses, such as just-so stories of ... why humans have less body hair than other apes, might not be falsifiable or simple to investigate within any epistemological framework"

## Pitfalls of adaptationism (2)

<#b2cols>

- microcephalin/ASPM [@williams_genes_2006]
- homozygous mutants are microcephalic
- evidence of ongoing **positive selection** (4000-5000 years)
- selected variant low-frequency in sub-Saharan Africa, high in Europeans (!!)
<#finalhandout
<#pause>
- **but** ...
    - mutations **don't** correlate with cognitive ability [@timpson_comment_2007]
    - brain size **unchanged** over 35,000 years
>

